{
  "texts": [
    "Thus, it emerges that two episodes are sufficient for transferring to the target building T inductive a DRL controller in heterogeneous inductive setting, since during the second cooling season the peak shaving limit was exceeded only 12 times out of 8640 observations, reducing the maximum peak value of energy withdrawn from the grid to 0.55 kWh.",
    "Furthermore, the online TL strategy revealed excellent performance in both electricity cost (E cost,TL = 34.3 €) and cumulative sum of temperature violations (T viol,TL = 17.2 °C).",
    "However, the offline DRL controller exceeded the peak shaving limit only two times out of 8640 observations since it relies on a more refined control policy as being trained on 30 episodes, reducing electricity cost by 50% (E cost,off-DRL = 16.5 €) but having poorer performance in terms of internal temperature control (T viol,Off-DRL = 96.3 °C) compared to online TL.",
    "Figures 10 and 11 reveal several similarities in how the energy system was managed by the offline DRL controller and the online TL controller after updating its control policies while actively managing the system two successive cooling seasons.",
    "Offline DRL and online TL approaches managed the system to withdraw energy from the grid during low-electricity price periods."
  ]
}